1
00:01:15,366 --> 00:01:18,438
IANNIS: How long have you
been deaf in this ear?

2
00:01:18,525 --> 00:01:20,880
STAMATIS: Since as long
as I can remember.

3
00:01:20,965 --> 00:01:22,115
-[Snip]
-Ow!

4
00:01:22,206 --> 00:01:23,480
MRS STAMATIS: Shut up!

5
00:01:23,566 --> 00:01:26,080
Keep still while the doctor
is examining you.

6
00:01:26,166 --> 00:01:27,884
IANNIS: I need a fish-hook...

7
00:01:27,966 --> 00:01:29,764
about the right size
for a mullet...

8
00:01:29,847 --> 00:01:32,838
with a long shank,
and a hammer.

9
00:01:32,926 --> 00:01:35,121
STAMATIS:
A fish-hook? A hammer?

10
00:01:35,206 --> 00:01:36,640
MRS STAMATIS:
Here's a fish-hook...

11
00:01:36,727 --> 00:01:38,445
and a hammer.

12
00:01:38,527 --> 00:01:40,995
IANNIS: Ahem.

13
00:01:41,087 --> 00:01:46,765
[Tapping]

14
00:01:46,848 --> 00:01:50,601
Right. Now keep still.

15
00:01:50,688 --> 00:01:51,837
[Pop]

16
00:01:51,928 --> 00:01:53,122
STAMATIS: Ow!

17
00:01:55,448 --> 00:01:57,279
IANNIS: A pea.

18
00:01:59,089 --> 00:02:01,966
It is very papilionaceous,
is it not?

19
00:02:02,048 --> 00:02:05,724
He must have stuck it
in his ear when he was a child.

20
00:02:05,809 --> 00:02:07,481
Oh, my God, it's loud.

21
00:02:07,569 --> 00:02:10,402
I mean, everything is loud.
My own voice is loud.

22
00:02:10,489 --> 00:02:14,881
Your deafness is cured.
A very satisfactory operation.

23
00:02:14,970 --> 00:02:16,368
I've had an operation?

24
00:02:16,449 --> 00:02:20,238
Ha! I'm the only person I know
who's had an operation.

25
00:02:20,330 --> 00:02:22,241
It feels as if my whole head...

26
00:02:22,330 --> 00:02:25,208
has filled up with spring water,
all cold and clear.

27
00:02:25,290 --> 00:02:26,804
Talk some sense
when the doctor...

28
00:02:26,891 --> 00:02:28,370
has been kind enough
to cure you.

29
00:02:28,451 --> 00:02:30,725
All these years
thinking you are deaf.

30
00:02:30,810 --> 00:02:34,690
But now there will be no excuses
when I ask you to remember...

31
00:02:34,771 --> 00:02:36,602
to collect something
on your way home.

32
00:02:36,691 --> 00:02:40,206
Or to stoke up the fire
before we go to church.

33
00:02:40,291 --> 00:02:41,805
[Bell ringing]

34
00:02:41,892 --> 00:02:43,610
MRS STAMATIS: Perhaps now
you will hear me...

35
00:02:43,692 --> 00:02:46,330
when I say to you,
"Mend the chair, Stamatis.

36
00:02:46,411 --> 00:02:48,448
"Fix the leaking roof,
Stamatis. "

37
00:02:48,532 --> 00:02:51,649
And now I won't have
to speak so loud...

38
00:03:01,972 --> 00:03:07,650
IANNIS: Antonio,
do you remember our island?

39
00:03:07,733 --> 00:03:10,885
It does not change.

40
00:03:10,974 --> 00:03:13,851
On the feast day
of Saint Gerasimos...

41
00:03:13,933 --> 00:03:16,242
we still bring our sick
to the holy place...

42
00:03:16,334 --> 00:03:20,247
and pray that
their suffering may cease.

43
00:03:22,814 --> 00:03:26,205
When Pelagia was a child,
I promised her...

44
00:03:26,295 --> 00:03:28,808
that I would write
a history of Cephallonia...

45
00:03:28,894 --> 00:03:34,253
but somehow I still
have not found the time.

46
00:03:34,335 --> 00:03:38,852
I wanted her to understand
how a land so peaceful...

47
00:03:38,936 --> 00:03:42,894
could be shattered
by earthquakes and war.

48
00:03:44,775 --> 00:03:46,767
I wanted her to understand...

49
00:03:46,856 --> 00:03:49,006
why sometimes
the gods bless us...

50
00:03:49,096 --> 00:03:53,010
and why they sometimes
become angry...

51
00:03:53,097 --> 00:03:59,172
and shake us,
and fill our lives with pain.

52
00:03:59,257 --> 00:04:03,853
I want her to learn the lesson
that nature teaches us.

53
00:04:03,937 --> 00:04:07,977
That we should not ask
why we are wounded...

54
00:04:08,058 --> 00:04:12,528
only if the wound
can be healed.

55
00:04:18,778 --> 00:04:20,735
[Speaking Greek]

56
00:04:25,218 --> 00:04:27,095
[Praying in Greek]

57
00:04:29,899 --> 00:04:32,971
A purely psychological
phenomenon.

58
00:04:33,059 --> 00:04:35,733
STAMATIS: How do you
explain the miracle?

59
00:04:35,820 --> 00:04:39,607
Can Lenin cure the mad?
Can Stalin heal the afflicted?

60
00:04:39,699 --> 00:04:42,339
It's obvious.
It's a set-up!

61
00:04:42,420 --> 00:04:44,615
To keep people
enslaved to religion.

62
00:04:44,700 --> 00:04:45,928
You don't have to shout.

63
00:04:46,020 --> 00:04:47,499
I'm not deaf.

64
00:04:48,780 --> 00:04:50,737
[Cheering]

65
00:04:54,100 --> 00:04:56,056
[Greek music playing]

66
00:05:28,783 --> 00:05:32,060
I want to see the cannon again.

67
00:05:32,144 --> 00:05:34,180
-Yeah!
-Cannon!

68
00:05:34,264 --> 00:05:37,494
All right.

69
00:05:37,583 --> 00:05:40,257
I will need stones
from the street.

70
00:05:40,344 --> 00:05:42,414
As many as you can find.

71
00:05:43,704 --> 00:05:45,023
Be right back.

72
00:05:46,705 --> 00:05:48,138
VELISARIOS: Ready, children?

73
00:05:48,225 --> 00:05:50,101
Cover your ears.

74
00:05:54,585 --> 00:05:56,064
[Cheering]

75
00:05:56,145 --> 00:06:00,583
[Yelling]

76
00:06:00,666 --> 00:06:03,783
Ow, that hurts!
Oh, that hurts!

77
00:06:09,786 --> 00:06:11,105
VELISARIOS: Will he die?

78
00:06:12,466 --> 00:06:15,698
Eventually, one of these days,
like all of us.

79
00:06:15,787 --> 00:06:17,106
Turn over.

80
00:06:26,827 --> 00:06:30,264
-Aah!
-Good, strong gluteals.

81
00:06:30,348 --> 00:06:32,066
-Pelagia.
-Hmm?

82
00:06:32,148 --> 00:06:33,899
Tell us about the gluteals.

83
00:06:33,987 --> 00:06:36,263
Please, come closer.
Have a good look.

84
00:06:36,348 --> 00:06:40,102
Fetch your friends.
Everybody's welcome.

85
00:06:40,188 --> 00:06:42,224
Gluteals.

86
00:06:42,308 --> 00:06:46,018
Maximus, medius, minimus.

87
00:06:46,109 --> 00:06:48,941
The maximus is the external
surface of the ilium...

88
00:06:49,028 --> 00:06:52,578
between anterior
and interior gluteal lines...

89
00:06:55,229 --> 00:06:56,423
DROSOULA: Mandras!

90
00:06:58,630 --> 00:06:59,779
Iatre...

91
00:06:59,870 --> 00:07:01,860
He'll be fine.

92
00:07:01,949 --> 00:07:05,420
They told me you were shot.
I thought I was going to die.

93
00:07:05,510 --> 00:07:07,865
I don't know why you can't
keep out of trouble!

94
00:07:07,950 --> 00:07:09,463
I don't know!

95
00:07:09,550 --> 00:07:12,543
Iatre, you should count yourself
lucky you don't have a son.

96
00:07:12,631 --> 00:07:16,384
Boys, they never grow up.
Look at me.

97
00:07:16,470 --> 00:07:19,508
Old before my time.

98
00:07:20,871 --> 00:07:23,101
MANDRAS: Aah! Aah!

99
00:07:25,271 --> 00:07:27,228
[Speaking Greek]

100
00:07:55,234 --> 00:07:56,587
It's too hot.

101
00:07:56,674 --> 00:07:59,745
The fish are all hiding
in the rocks...

102
00:07:59,833 --> 00:08:02,871
or keeping cool
at the bottom of the sea.

103
00:08:06,834 --> 00:08:09,872
Aah! No, Mandras!

104
00:08:09,955 --> 00:08:11,593
[Laughing] Aah!

105
00:08:11,675 --> 00:08:13,744
No! Put me down! Put me down!

106
00:08:13,834 --> 00:08:16,064
-Waah!
-Aah!

107
00:08:16,155 --> 00:08:17,986
-Whoo!
-Aah!

108
00:08:18,075 --> 00:08:20,031
[Laughing]

109
00:08:24,196 --> 00:08:25,515
Ha ha!

110
00:08:36,036 --> 00:08:37,515
that a Greek battleship,
the Eli...

111
00:08:37,597 --> 00:08:39,394
has been torpedoed
by an Italian submarine...

112
00:08:39,477 --> 00:08:42,627
despite the fact that Greece
is not yet involved in the war.

113
00:08:42,716 --> 00:08:45,470
Prime Minister Metaxas
has protested strongly...

114
00:08:45,557 --> 00:08:47,149
to Mussolini's government
in Rome...

115
00:08:47,237 --> 00:08:50,229
which has denied
responsibility for the attack.

116
00:08:50,317 --> 00:08:52,149
And there are continued
reports of fighting...

117
00:08:52,238 --> 00:08:53,990
between Greek
and Italian soldiers...

118
00:08:54,078 --> 00:08:55,908
on the Greek-Albanian border.

119
00:08:55,997 --> 00:08:57,555
But in Athens this morning...

120
00:08:57,637 --> 00:08:59,071
the Italian ambassador
once again denied...

121
00:08:59,158 --> 00:09:00,716
What are they saying?

122
00:09:00,798 --> 00:09:03,995
The Italians are in Albania,
close to the border.

123
00:09:04,078 --> 00:09:05,875
They have reported
some fighting.

124
00:09:05,958 --> 00:09:07,551
There! You hear that?

125
00:09:07,639 --> 00:09:10,198
They are saying they are
not about to declare war.

126
00:09:10,278 --> 00:09:11,472
There. What did I say?

127
00:09:11,558 --> 00:09:13,311
They want to catch us sleeping.

128
00:09:13,399 --> 00:09:15,833
They want to creep up on us
in the dead of night!

129
00:09:15,919 --> 00:09:18,717
-You filthy liar!
-Your father was a goat!

130
00:09:18,799 --> 00:09:21,360
Shut up!

131
00:09:21,440 --> 00:09:23,112
If you two don't stop
trading insults...

132
00:09:23,200 --> 00:09:25,155
I'm going to start
taking coffee at home.

133
00:09:28,240 --> 00:09:29,832
[Footsteps]

134
00:09:29,920 --> 00:09:32,912
PELAGIA:
Mandras wants to marry me.

135
00:09:33,000 --> 00:09:35,595
I told him
he'd have to ask you.

136
00:09:35,681 --> 00:09:37,637
IANNIS:
I don't want to marry him.

137
00:09:37,721 --> 00:09:40,280
You don't like him.

138
00:09:40,360 --> 00:09:42,431
You are both too young.

139
00:09:42,521 --> 00:09:46,070
Everyone is too young
when they marry.

140
00:09:46,161 --> 00:09:47,958
I have often thought
that you would...

141
00:09:48,041 --> 00:09:49,600
only ever be able
to marry happily...

142
00:09:49,682 --> 00:09:51,673
with a foreigner.

143
00:09:51,762 --> 00:09:53,240
BOTH: A dentist from Norway...

144
00:09:53,321 --> 00:09:55,312
...or something.

145
00:09:57,682 --> 00:10:02,039
Mandras is not your equal,
and he would expect...

146
00:10:02,122 --> 00:10:04,557
to be better than his wife.

147
00:10:04,643 --> 00:10:08,112
He is a man, after all.

148
00:10:08,202 --> 00:10:11,001
I will tell you now
what I will say to him.

149
00:10:11,083 --> 00:10:14,200
I am not giving away a dowry.

150
00:10:15,683 --> 00:10:17,401
Who marries without a dowry?

151
00:10:17,483 --> 00:10:19,440
You should marry for love.

152
00:10:19,524 --> 00:10:20,798
I love Mandras.

153
00:10:23,083 --> 00:10:25,757
So what am I supposed to do?

154
00:10:25,844 --> 00:10:27,436
Go off
to Mandras' mother's house...

155
00:10:27,524 --> 00:10:29,594
with nothing
but a bag of clothes?

156
00:10:29,684 --> 00:10:32,643
Oh, and my goat.

157
00:10:32,725 --> 00:10:34,522
I'll never be able
to show my face.

158
00:10:34,605 --> 00:10:37,072
I'll be the laughing stock
of Cephallonia.

159
00:10:37,164 --> 00:10:39,599
You can imagine
how people will talk.

160
00:10:39,685 --> 00:10:42,597
I don't know
how you will bear the shame.

161
00:10:42,685 --> 00:10:46,759
There is going to be a war.
Terrible things happen in wars.

162
00:10:46,846 --> 00:10:49,440
Use this to defend yourself.

163
00:10:49,526 --> 00:10:52,995
And, if necessary,
use it against yourself.

164
00:10:53,085 --> 00:10:55,156
Your marriage
will have to wait.

165
00:10:57,766 --> 00:10:59,404
I look around me.

166
00:10:59,486 --> 00:11:02,524
I see fishermen.
I see farmers.

167
00:11:02,607 --> 00:11:06,121
I see strong, healthy men
who are born free.

168
00:11:06,206 --> 00:11:09,438
But today your freedom
is in danger.

169
00:11:09,527 --> 00:11:11,916
The Italian Army
sweeps through Albania...

170
00:11:12,007 --> 00:11:16,126
and her troops get ready to
cross the frontiers of Greece.

171
00:11:16,208 --> 00:11:17,482
Exo Mussolini!

172
00:11:17,568 --> 00:11:20,286
CROWD: Exo Mussolini!

173
00:11:20,367 --> 00:11:22,120
OFFICER: If you care
about your country...

174
00:11:22,208 --> 00:11:24,199
then you must fight
to defend her.

175
00:11:24,288 --> 00:11:26,119
Join the war in Albania.

176
00:11:26,208 --> 00:11:28,802
Fight for your mothers,
your sweethearts...

177
00:11:28,889 --> 00:11:30,925
your wives, your children.

178
00:11:31,009 --> 00:11:33,806
Fight for the freedom
for all Greek people...

179
00:11:33,888 --> 00:11:36,801
to live their lives
with dignity and respect!

180
00:11:36,889 --> 00:11:38,845
[Shouting in Greek]

181
00:11:44,570 --> 00:11:47,037
[Priest speaking Greek]

182
00:12:06,091 --> 00:12:07,922
MANDRAS: When I come back
from the war...

183
00:12:08,011 --> 00:12:10,286
we will get married.

184
00:12:10,371 --> 00:12:13,045
And I will build a house
for Pelagia...

185
00:12:13,132 --> 00:12:16,248
on the land
that belonged to my father.

186
00:12:26,253 --> 00:12:29,370
[Priest speaking Greek]

187
00:12:36,853 --> 00:12:38,809
[Singing in Greek]

188
00:13:01,855 --> 00:13:03,971
I know we are different.

189
00:13:04,055 --> 00:13:07,172
I don't know about the world.

190
00:13:07,255 --> 00:13:11,010
Where have I been?
What could I know?

191
00:13:11,096 --> 00:13:14,485
I don't know how to say
what I feel inside.

192
00:13:14,575 --> 00:13:16,009
I don't know how to tell you...

193
00:13:16,096 --> 00:13:19,691
what is in here.
But I think...

194
00:13:19,776 --> 00:13:25,295
I know...Pelagia...

195
00:13:25,377 --> 00:13:29,608
I love you.

196
00:13:29,696 --> 00:13:31,415
[Cheering]

197
00:13:38,618 --> 00:13:42,371
Tomorrow I leave for the war.

198
00:13:42,457 --> 00:13:46,133
Pelagia, come and dance with me.

199
00:13:48,218 --> 00:13:51,176
[Laughter]

200
00:13:51,258 --> 00:13:53,011
[Yelling in Greek]

201
00:14:15,860 --> 00:14:17,816
[Bell ringing]

202
00:14:55,182 --> 00:14:57,538
I'll write. I promise.

203
00:14:59,263 --> 00:15:01,299
And promise that
you will write to me.

204
00:15:04,544 --> 00:15:07,535
[Speaking Greek]

205
00:15:24,024 --> 00:15:26,255
PELAGIA: "My darling,
you have not written...

206
00:15:26,345 --> 00:15:28,813
"since that day I saw you off.

207
00:15:28,905 --> 00:15:30,657
"And I am so terrified...

208
00:15:30,745 --> 00:15:33,021
"that I am not getting
any letters from you...

209
00:15:33,106 --> 00:15:37,018
"because you have been
wounded or taken prisoner.

210
00:15:37,105 --> 00:15:40,098
"And I have nightmares
that you are dead. "

211
00:15:43,146 --> 00:15:45,023
"Summer has turned to winter...

212
00:15:45,106 --> 00:15:49,657
"and I am writing
my hundredth letter to you.

213
00:15:49,746 --> 00:15:51,737
"The wounded
who have returned...

214
00:15:51,826 --> 00:15:54,421
"bring news
of terrible conditions.

215
00:15:54,507 --> 00:15:58,136
"Freezing cold, no food.

216
00:15:58,227 --> 00:16:00,298
"But they bring
no news from you. "

217
00:16:04,707 --> 00:16:07,381
"Every day I wait
for the mail from Argostoli...

218
00:16:07,468 --> 00:16:09,823
"and every day
there is nothing.

219
00:16:09,908 --> 00:16:12,866
"And I feel
as if I am going mad...

220
00:16:12,948 --> 00:16:17,022
"with worry and fear.
I try not to lose hope...

221
00:16:17,109 --> 00:16:21,819
"but I long to feel something,
even if it is only pain. "

222
00:16:21,909 --> 00:16:24,423
[Speaking Greek]

223
00:16:24,509 --> 00:16:26,465
[Sobbing]

224
00:16:45,831 --> 00:16:47,821
We won!

225
00:16:47,910 --> 00:16:49,468
We won!

226
00:16:51,511 --> 00:16:53,741
It's over!

227
00:16:53,831 --> 00:16:56,299
We've beaten them in Albania.

228
00:16:56,391 --> 00:16:57,825
Look!

229
00:16:57,912 --> 00:17:00,790
8,000 of us
against 14,000 Italians...

230
00:17:00,871 --> 00:17:02,623
and we forced them to withdraw.

231
00:17:05,592 --> 00:17:07,947
What?

232
00:17:08,032 --> 00:17:11,742
Hitler will never let
his lapdog be humiliated.

233
00:17:11,833 --> 00:17:13,983
He will come to Mussolini's aid.

234
00:17:19,033 --> 00:17:21,228
PELAGIA: "I have written
this letter a dozen times...

235
00:17:21,313 --> 00:17:24,862
"and a dozen times
I have thrown it away.

236
00:17:24,953 --> 00:17:28,629
"I don't know how
to describe my feelings.

237
00:17:28,714 --> 00:17:32,023
"It's as if I've been
waiting a hundred years...

238
00:17:32,113 --> 00:17:33,991
"to hear from you.

239
00:17:34,074 --> 00:17:36,872
"Waiting a hundred years
for you to return. "

240
00:17:44,034 --> 00:17:45,592
Pelagia?

241
00:17:48,435 --> 00:17:50,153
This is hopeless.

242
00:17:50,235 --> 00:17:52,669
It's all wrong!

243
00:17:58,955 --> 00:17:59,831
NEWSREEL ANNOUNCER:
Following the great defeat...

244
00:18:00,275 --> 00:18:01,675
of the Italians in Albania...

245
00:18:01,756 --> 00:18:03,155
Hitler's bombers
have counterattacked...

246
00:18:03,236 --> 00:18:04,749
and the German Army
has driven a path...

247
00:18:04,836 --> 00:18:07,066
through to
the Greek capital, Athens.

248
00:18:07,156 --> 00:18:08,988
A large number of Greek ships
were destroyed...

249
00:18:09,077 --> 00:18:12,069
in the bombing of the nearby
Port of Piraeus.

250
00:18:12,157 --> 00:18:14,386
On April 27, the Athenian
Military Commissioner...

251
00:18:14,476 --> 00:18:17,230
General Calvacos, officially
handed over the keys...

252
00:18:17,317 --> 00:18:19,035
of the ancient city
to his German counterpart...

253
00:18:19,117 --> 00:18:20,948
Lieutenant Colonel
Von Zephyr...

254
00:18:21,037 --> 00:18:22,311
and preparations
are underway...

255
00:18:22,397 --> 00:18:24,195
for a carve-up
of the territory.

256
00:18:24,278 --> 00:18:26,155
Hitler retains
direct control...

257
00:18:26,238 --> 00:18:28,307
of much of northern Greece,
including Salonica...

258
00:18:28,397 --> 00:18:29,910
and the southern island
of Crete.

259
00:18:29,997 --> 00:18:31,829
The rest of Greece
will be under the control...

260
00:18:31,918 --> 00:18:33,590
of Hitler's ally, Mussolini...

261
00:18:33,678 --> 00:18:36,317
though the Germans will retain
the final authority.

262
00:18:54,360 --> 00:18:56,315
[Men shouting]

263
00:19:59,564 --> 00:20:02,476
Bella bambina at two o'clock!

264
00:20:02,564 --> 00:20:04,521
[Speaking Italian]

265
00:20:21,485 --> 00:20:23,396
[Pounding on door]

266
00:20:37,926 --> 00:20:39,201
Captain Corelli.

267
00:20:46,008 --> 00:20:47,202
Ahem.

268
00:20:47,288 --> 00:20:48,687
"Fuck off."

269
00:20:48,768 --> 00:20:51,565
[Laughter]

270
00:20:57,488 --> 00:20:59,763
Have him tell the mayor
that unless we receive...

271
00:20:59,848 --> 00:21:02,443
the surrender of the town's
authorities in five minutes...

272
00:21:02,529 --> 00:21:05,281
we'll mobilise our troops
and storm the building.

273
00:21:06,928 --> 00:21:11,207
The mayor says if you don't
know what "fuck off" means...

274
00:21:11,289 --> 00:21:13,883
then come inside
and we'll show you.

275
00:21:20,769 --> 00:21:22,726
[Speaking Italian]

276
00:21:34,370 --> 00:21:38,444
"We refuse to surrender
to a nation...

277
00:21:38,531 --> 00:21:40,920
"that we have defeated
in Albania...

278
00:21:41,011 --> 00:21:43,685
"and we reserve the right
to surrender...

279
00:21:43,772 --> 00:21:46,808
"to a German officer
of significant rank.

280
00:21:46,891 --> 00:21:48,290
"So fuck off."

281
00:22:25,054 --> 00:22:27,694
Who is this? Who are you?

282
00:22:27,775 --> 00:22:30,129
-[Clicks heels]
-Captain Gunter Weber.

283
00:22:30,214 --> 00:22:32,205
Liaison officer
with the Grenadiers at Lixouri.

284
00:22:32,294 --> 00:22:35,844
"Captain" is not what we
would call a significant rank.

285
00:22:35,935 --> 00:22:37,368
CORELLI:
There are only 200 Germans...

286
00:22:37,455 --> 00:22:38,808
on the island,
and Captain Weber...

287
00:22:38,895 --> 00:22:41,888
is the highest ranking officer
amongst them.

288
00:22:41,976 --> 00:22:44,728
[Speaking softly in Greek]

289
00:22:51,416 --> 00:22:54,454
Our decision
is that surrendering...

290
00:22:54,537 --> 00:22:57,335
to Captain Weber's dog
is more appropriate...

291
00:22:57,417 --> 00:23:00,567
than surrendering to an Italian.

292
00:23:31,739 --> 00:23:33,695
[Singing Verdi's "Anvil Chorus"
in Italian]

293
00:23:35,699 --> 00:23:41,774
ALL: Chi del gitano
i giorni abbella

294
00:23:41,859 --> 00:23:47,014
Chi del gitano
i giorni abbella

295
00:23:47,100 --> 00:23:51,891
Chi i giorni abbella

296
00:23:53,821 --> 00:23:56,254
Carlo Guercio
reporting for duty, sir.

297
00:23:56,340 --> 00:23:59,538
-Carlo, where have you served?
-Albania.

298
00:23:59,621 --> 00:24:01,213
Albania?

299
00:24:01,301 --> 00:24:03,895
None of us have seen
any action yet.

300
00:24:03,981 --> 00:24:05,300
I was with the Julia Division.

301
00:24:09,981 --> 00:24:11,733
Ah.

302
00:24:11,821 --> 00:24:14,416
Then you have fought enough
for all of us.

303
00:24:14,502 --> 00:24:16,777
Carlo, can you sing?

304
00:24:16,862 --> 00:24:18,853
Let's hear you sing.

305
00:24:18,942 --> 00:24:22,299
O mio babbino, caro

306
00:24:22,383 --> 00:24:30,973
Mi piace bello

307
00:24:31,063 --> 00:24:33,418
Bello

308
00:24:34,384 --> 00:24:35,863
No matter.

309
00:24:35,944 --> 00:24:39,652
Everyone in our battery is
a member of the opera society.

310
00:24:39,743 --> 00:24:41,974
These are the rules
of engagement.

311
00:24:42,064 --> 00:24:45,613
One, all those called
to regular musical fatigues...

312
00:24:45,704 --> 00:24:47,820
shall be obliged to play
a musical instrument.

313
00:24:47,904 --> 00:24:49,577
Uh, spoons, the helmet...

314
00:24:49,665 --> 00:24:52,622
comb, paper,
and so on, and so on.

315
00:24:52,704 --> 00:24:54,103
Two, anyone who says...

316
00:24:54,184 --> 00:24:56,699
that Donizetti is better
than Verdi shall be required

317
00:24:56,785 --> 00:25:00,221
to sing "Funiculi Funicula"
and other songs about railways.

318
00:25:00,305 --> 00:25:03,343
Three, um...

319
00:25:03,426 --> 00:25:06,303
three, um...ah.

320
00:25:13,146 --> 00:25:15,865
This is an outrage!
Quite impossible.

321
00:25:15,946 --> 00:25:17,938
It's out of the question.

322
00:25:18,027 --> 00:25:19,938
Sir, the fact is,
I'm sorry to say...

323
00:25:20,027 --> 00:25:22,221
and with great regret,
that my orders are...

324
00:25:22,306 --> 00:25:23,819
to billet an officer
in your home.

325
00:25:23,906 --> 00:25:26,296
I am a doctor.
This is my surgery.

326
00:25:26,387 --> 00:25:27,661
I don't have room for guests!

327
00:25:27,747 --> 00:25:30,181
-Sir, these are my orders!
-I don't care!

328
00:25:30,267 --> 00:25:32,543
I don't recognise
your authority!

329
00:25:36,347 --> 00:25:39,624
Wait a minute.

330
00:25:39,708 --> 00:25:42,780
What is wrong with your feet?

331
00:25:42,868 --> 00:25:44,381
I have terrible corns.

332
00:25:44,468 --> 00:25:46,027
My boots are killing me.

333
00:25:46,109 --> 00:25:47,428
You are a quartermaster.

334
00:25:47,509 --> 00:25:50,500
You must have access
to medical supplies.

335
00:25:50,588 --> 00:25:54,264
To treat your corns,
I will need morphine...

336
00:25:54,349 --> 00:25:56,305
hypodermic syringes,
sulphur ointment...

337
00:25:56,389 --> 00:25:58,425
surgical spirit, neosalvarsan.

338
00:25:58,509 --> 00:26:00,307
Iodine, scalpels, cullodian...

339
00:26:00,390 --> 00:26:02,620
bandages, lint.

340
00:26:02,710 --> 00:26:05,177
Perhaps your officer
could bring supplies...

341
00:26:05,269 --> 00:26:06,702
when he comes.

342
00:26:25,871 --> 00:26:28,101
My father is not here.

343
00:26:29,672 --> 00:26:31,867
He'll be home this evening.

344
00:26:34,111 --> 00:26:36,672
You don't even know who I am.

345
00:26:42,993 --> 00:26:44,312
Mandras?

346
00:26:45,993 --> 00:26:50,111
I walked all the way...
from Epirus.

347
00:26:50,193 --> 00:26:51,592
No boots.

348
00:26:55,873 --> 00:26:58,342
I wrote to you every day.

349
00:26:58,434 --> 00:27:00,901
A hundred letters.

350
00:27:00,993 --> 00:27:03,746
And not a single reply.

351
00:27:06,834 --> 00:27:09,587
I never learned...

352
00:27:09,674 --> 00:27:12,143
to read or write.

353
00:27:15,234 --> 00:27:20,263
Oh, Lord, what a stench.
It's worse than pigs.

354
00:27:20,355 --> 00:27:23,108
You see, Pelagia, what a state
these men get into...

355
00:27:23,195 --> 00:27:25,106
when there are no women
to look after them.

356
00:27:25,195 --> 00:27:27,756
And I don't care
if he's been to war.

357
00:27:27,836 --> 00:27:33,069
If we catch his fleas and lice,
I'm going to skin him alive.

358
00:27:33,156 --> 00:27:35,795
Ammonia, oil of sassafras,
and zinc for scabies.

359
00:27:37,756 --> 00:27:42,148
You're a woman and--
and you know so many things.

360
00:27:42,237 --> 00:27:45,706
At least you can see
what you are getting.

361
00:27:45,796 --> 00:27:47,753
Not much of a bargain, is he?

362
00:27:47,837 --> 00:27:50,670
You fall in love
with the person, not the body.

363
00:27:50,757 --> 00:27:53,874
Love enters by the eyes
and also leaves by the eyes.

364
00:27:53,957 --> 00:27:55,311
Take it from me.

365
00:27:57,158 --> 00:28:00,035
We beat the Italians.
We had them running.

366
00:28:00,117 --> 00:28:02,473
[Panting]

367
00:28:02,558 --> 00:28:04,514
But we couldn't
fight the Germans.

368
00:28:15,318 --> 00:28:18,038
IANNIS: If I could cook...

369
00:28:18,119 --> 00:28:21,031
I would exchange jobs with you.

370
00:28:24,240 --> 00:28:26,548
In fact, I might retire.

371
00:28:45,921 --> 00:28:47,513
CORELLI: Bella bambina!

372
00:28:48,881 --> 00:28:50,872
Forgive me. Forgive me.

373
00:28:50,961 --> 00:28:52,918
I don't mean to embarrass you.

374
00:28:53,002 --> 00:28:55,151
I'm Captain Antonio Corelli...

375
00:28:55,241 --> 00:28:58,359
and that man
is one of our heroes.

376
00:28:58,442 --> 00:29:01,081
He has a hundred medals
for saving life...

377
00:29:01,162 --> 00:29:02,356
and none for taking it.

378
00:29:02,442 --> 00:29:04,319
A brave Italian
is a freak of nature.

379
00:29:04,402 --> 00:29:06,314
Said like a true Greek patriot.

380
00:29:06,403 --> 00:29:08,359
Captain Corelli?

381
00:29:08,443 --> 00:29:10,717
I want a word with you. Now.

382
00:29:10,802 --> 00:29:12,759
I want an explanation.

383
00:29:12,843 --> 00:29:15,562
I want to know why
you have defaced the monument.

384
00:29:15,643 --> 00:29:16,792
What monument?

385
00:29:16,883 --> 00:29:18,714
You have changed
the inscription to Latin.

386
00:29:18,803 --> 00:29:21,796
Do you think you can
so easily erase our history?

387
00:29:21,884 --> 00:29:24,795
Is this how you wage war?
By the chipping away of letters?

388
00:29:24,883 --> 00:29:26,032
I must protest.

389
00:29:26,123 --> 00:29:27,762
You cannot protest.
There is no excuse.

390
00:29:27,844 --> 00:29:30,881
I was about to protest because
I was not responsible for it.

391
00:29:30,964 --> 00:29:32,682
Pathetic.

392
00:29:34,245 --> 00:29:37,442
If you could tell me
where I'm going to sleep...

393
00:29:37,525 --> 00:29:38,923
In my daughter's room.

394
00:29:39,004 --> 00:29:41,235
But where will
your daughter sleep?

395
00:29:41,325 --> 00:29:43,043
It's none of your business
where I sleep.

396
00:29:43,125 --> 00:29:45,116
Ah. Tonight I'll sleep
in the yard.

397
00:29:45,205 --> 00:29:47,639
Tomorrow I'll request
alternative accommodation.

398
00:29:47,725 --> 00:29:49,717
I have made an arrangement
with your quartermaster.

399
00:29:49,806 --> 00:29:52,080
You are staying here
whether you like it or not.

400
00:29:52,165 --> 00:29:54,599
But your daughter's bed,
I feel it would not be--

401
00:29:54,685 --> 00:29:56,199
I don't care how you feel.

402
00:29:56,286 --> 00:29:58,322
That is not my problem.

403
00:29:58,406 --> 00:30:01,762
I am not the aggressor.
You understand me?

404
00:30:11,007 --> 00:30:13,965
This is very good.

405
00:30:14,047 --> 00:30:15,639
This is Cephallonian meat pie.

406
00:30:15,727 --> 00:30:18,037
Except that,
thanks to you people...

407
00:30:18,128 --> 00:30:20,198
it doesn't have any meat in it.

408
00:30:21,927 --> 00:30:23,838
I could bring some food.

409
00:30:23,928 --> 00:30:26,522
A little wine,
perhaps some panettone.

410
00:30:26,608 --> 00:30:29,042
We don't accept food
from the enemy.

411
00:30:29,128 --> 00:30:31,165
Maybe a little panettone.

412
00:30:35,968 --> 00:30:38,642
I am going for a walk.

413
00:30:38,729 --> 00:30:41,482
The curfew starts
in one hour's time.

414
00:30:41,569 --> 00:30:44,288
I was born here.

415
00:30:44,369 --> 00:30:46,167
This is my island.

416
00:30:54,490 --> 00:30:57,368
Aren't you going
to go and arrest him?

417
00:30:57,450 --> 00:31:00,966
He's defying you,
ignoring the curfew.

418
00:31:01,051 --> 00:31:02,962
You're absolutely right.

419
00:31:03,051 --> 00:31:06,087
Quick, get the gun.
Somebody shoot him, shoot him.

420
00:31:06,170 --> 00:31:08,480
Ha ha ha ha ha!

421
00:31:29,253 --> 00:31:30,402
Armare!

422
00:31:30,493 --> 00:31:32,528
[Men yelling]

423
00:31:32,612 --> 00:31:36,322
Direzione uno-tre-due.

424
00:31:39,173 --> 00:31:43,406
Alto uno-zèro-cinque.

425
00:31:43,494 --> 00:31:47,645
Capitano Antonio Corelli.

426
00:31:47,733 --> 00:31:49,086
Now you try.

427
00:31:49,173 --> 00:31:52,007
Capitano Antonio Corelli.

428
00:31:52,094 --> 00:31:53,322
PELAGIA: Lemoni!

429
00:31:53,414 --> 00:31:55,848
Babibaba Finono Kalikali.

430
00:31:55,934 --> 00:31:58,813
CORELLI: Oh, what? Babibaba?

431
00:31:58,895 --> 00:32:03,490
Ha ha ha! Capitano.

432
00:32:03,574 --> 00:32:04,724
LEMONI: Capitano.

433
00:32:04,815 --> 00:32:05,964
Sì. Antonio.

434
00:32:06,055 --> 00:32:07,204
Lemoni.

435
00:32:07,295 --> 00:32:08,523
LEMONI: Antonio.

436
00:32:08,615 --> 00:32:10,571
-Corelli.
-Go home.

437
00:32:10,655 --> 00:32:13,728
Go on.
You can come back later.

438
00:32:16,775 --> 00:32:19,893
Signorina...

439
00:32:19,976 --> 00:32:23,173
in times of war,
we have to make the most...

440
00:32:23,256 --> 00:32:25,976
of what little
innocent pleasure there is.

441
00:32:31,296 --> 00:32:34,209
PELAGIA: "I have started
to make a waistcoat for you.

442
00:32:34,297 --> 00:32:39,212
"Eagles and flowers,
embroidered with gold thread.

443
00:32:39,297 --> 00:32:41,858
"But I can't seem
to get them to match up.

444
00:32:41,938 --> 00:32:44,053
"One flower is much bigger.

445
00:32:44,137 --> 00:32:47,813
"One eagle is in a different
place from the other.

446
00:32:47,898 --> 00:32:51,254
"And when I try to make them
more even, it gets worse.

447
00:32:51,338 --> 00:32:53,249
"I just can't get it right."

448
00:32:53,338 --> 00:32:55,614
MANDRAS:
You could kill him, you know.

449
00:32:57,658 --> 00:33:00,775
He's the enemy.
You could poison him.

450
00:33:00,858 --> 00:33:02,770
No one would ever
know how he died.

451
00:33:04,379 --> 00:33:08,214
Dimitris and Spiros have both
left to join the partisans.

452
00:33:08,300 --> 00:33:11,053
They've gone by boat to Patra.

453
00:33:11,140 --> 00:33:13,892
And who knows where from there.

454
00:33:13,979 --> 00:33:15,698
I should be with them.

455
00:33:15,780 --> 00:33:17,816
You're not going anywhere
until you are strong again.

456
00:33:22,220 --> 00:33:25,019
Read the last one.

457
00:33:25,101 --> 00:33:27,455
The last letter you wrote
before I came home.

458
00:33:35,581 --> 00:33:39,177
"My darling,
I've heard nothing from you...

459
00:33:39,262 --> 00:33:41,650
'for such a long time...

460
00:33:41,741 --> 00:33:43,972
"and I feel desperate
and helpless...

461
00:33:44,062 --> 00:33:47,054
"and I am burning my brains
with worry.

462
00:33:47,142 --> 00:33:49,258
'Yesterday I wrote you
such a long letter...

463
00:33:49,342 --> 00:33:51,061
"that said everything
perfectly...

464
00:33:51,143 --> 00:33:52,656
-"and believe it--"
-Listen.

465
00:33:52,743 --> 00:33:55,381
[Trucks rumbling]

466
00:33:58,703 --> 00:34:00,022
Mandras!

467
00:34:16,224 --> 00:34:18,180
MANDRAS: I can't stay here.

468
00:34:24,264 --> 00:34:26,220
[Singing in Italian]

469
00:34:37,186 --> 00:34:40,257
Signorina. Signorina.

470
00:34:40,345 --> 00:34:42,382
You are drunk.

471
00:34:42,466 --> 00:34:44,024
Yes, I confess.

472
00:34:44,106 --> 00:34:46,381
We have been
drinking, singing...

473
00:34:46,466 --> 00:34:48,662
generally misbehaving.

474
00:34:48,747 --> 00:34:51,341
I thought you were a soldier.

475
00:34:51,427 --> 00:34:53,656
Captain Antonio Corelli,
33rd Regiment, Artillery...

476
00:34:53,746 --> 00:34:55,305
reporting for duty!

477
00:34:57,027 --> 00:34:58,938
Is everything a joke to you?

478
00:34:59,027 --> 00:35:00,619
[Sighs]

479
00:35:00,707 --> 00:35:03,666
No. Not everything.

480
00:35:13,148 --> 00:35:16,106
Captain Corelli,
I think this would be...

481
00:35:16,188 --> 00:35:18,908
a good time to hear you
play the mandolin.

482
00:35:22,388 --> 00:35:25,506
[Tapping]

483
00:35:35,389 --> 00:35:37,857
What on earth are you doing?

484
00:35:40,390 --> 00:35:43,063
I was just about to start.

485
00:35:43,150 --> 00:35:44,742
Well, about time, too,
I should think.

486
00:35:44,830 --> 00:35:48,619
The first 45 1/2 bars
are for the orchestra.

487
00:35:48,711 --> 00:35:51,178
"Allegro moderato e grazioso."

488
00:35:51,270 --> 00:35:53,660
You have to imagine
the orchestra.

489
00:35:53,751 --> 00:35:56,390
I'm damned if I can sit through
all that tapping again.

490
00:35:56,471 --> 00:35:58,109
Just play your part.

491
00:35:58,191 --> 00:36:00,148
CORELLI: If I do that,
I'll start getting confused...

492
00:36:00,232 --> 00:36:01,711
about when I'm
supposed to come in...

493
00:36:01,792 --> 00:36:05,500
and that, in a concert hall,
would be a disaster.

494
00:36:05,591 --> 00:36:08,629
I apologise
for disrupting the concert.

495
00:36:08,712 --> 00:36:11,704
I apologise to each
and every one of you.

496
00:36:11,792 --> 00:36:14,865
To those in the cheapest seats
in the gods...

497
00:36:14,953 --> 00:36:17,262
to Your Majesties
in your royal boxes...

498
00:36:17,352 --> 00:36:22,063
draped in your jewellery
and your fine furs.

499
00:36:22,153 --> 00:36:24,986
But I'm damned
if I can imagine an orchestra.

500
00:36:26,513 --> 00:36:28,232
I am going to bed.

501
00:36:34,193 --> 00:36:37,630
[Playing Hummel's
"Mandolin Concerto"]

502
00:37:35,398 --> 00:37:38,310
MANDRAS: Is this where
the captain sleeps?

503
00:37:40,919 --> 00:37:43,193
I was coming to see you.

504
00:37:45,118 --> 00:37:46,677
I'm leaving, Pelagia.

505
00:37:48,439 --> 00:37:49,588
In the morning.

506
00:37:49,679 --> 00:37:51,715
I'll take my boat to Astakos.

507
00:37:51,799 --> 00:37:54,439
-It's not safe.
-I'm a fisherman.

508
00:37:54,520 --> 00:37:57,159
I know those waters
like the back of my hand.

509
00:37:57,239 --> 00:37:59,514
I don't want you to go.

510
00:37:59,599 --> 00:38:04,833
If I die,
I won't have died for nothing.

511
00:38:04,920 --> 00:38:08,311
And if I live, I'll walk
with my head held high...

512
00:38:08,401 --> 00:38:11,234
for the rest of my life,
and everyone will say...

513
00:38:11,321 --> 00:38:15,599
"That's Mandras, who fought
for his country in the war."

514
00:38:18,081 --> 00:38:21,790
